  <body>
    <segment id="1" parent="14" relname="span">To Jef Raskin intuitiveness equals familiar (Communications of the ACM. 37:9, September 1994, pg. 17), </segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="1" relname="elaboration">
he stated that many products claim intuitiveness but when examined they fail, </segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="1" relname="elaboration">
he suggested that the term intuitiveness should be replaced with the word familiar discourse. </segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="1" relname="elaboration">
He defined intuitive as uses readily transferred existing skills. </segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="13" relname="span">
I tend to agree with Raskin, </segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="4" relname="concession">
I have not yet seen any information system package that can be used by new users without referring to help or manuals </segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="12" relname="span">
but on the other hand there is no doubt that the number of times the user has to reference help screens increases with decreasing intuitiveness, </segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="4" relname="elaboration">
that is, decreasing familiarity. </segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="11" relname="conjunction">
Intuitiveness plays an important role in usability</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="11" relname="conjunction"> and when designed properly leads to better usable products.</segment>
